[3] Russia (Stavrapol)
Date 1 Nov 2013
Source: Stavropol TV [in Russian, trans. Mod.CP, edited]
http://www.stavropolye.tv/medical/view/62702


The diagnosis of 27 cases of suspected measles, including 17 children in the Stavropol Region during the month of October 2013 indicated that an outbreak of measles virus infection was imminent.

According to the website STRC "Stavropol" on Friday [1 Nov 2013], the press service of the Regional Ministry of Health announced laboratory confirmation of the diagnosis in 11 of these cases. Virtually all the affected individuals had not been vaccinated.

Meanwhile, doctors throughout the cities and districts of the region initiated a number of measures aimed at preventing further spread of the disease. According to the Regional Ministry of Health, outbreaks of infection had occurred in neighbouring regions as a consequence of incomplete vaccine coverage of both adults and children, resulting in multiple epidemic foci. In contrast, the Stavropol region has maintained an annual routine measles vaccination programme, achieving at least 95 percent coverage. However, some adults and children had avoided or declined vaccination, creating a risk of outbreaks of infection.

Vaccination is the only effective measure to protect against this dangerous disease. Measles is transmitted by airborne droplets. Susceptibility to it is very high. Clinically, measles virus infection is accompanied by fever, runny nose, and conjunctivitis. On the 4th or 5th day after infection, a rash appears. Possible complications are pneumonia, encephalitis, otitis [inflammation/infection of the ear], laryngitis, stomatitis [inflammation in the mouth], keratitis [corneal/eye inflammation], etc. At present, a complex of preventive and control activities have been initiated, including home visits. Adults and children found to be at risk will be vaccinated, either at home or at their place of work.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Unusually, the people at risk of infection have not been identified as either immigrants or members of the Roma population.

The Stavropol Region [Krai] is a federal administrative region of Russia in the North Caucasian Federal District. Its administrative center is the city of Stavropol, population: 2 786 281 (2010 Census). A map locating the Stavropol Region can be accessed at: http://russiatrek.org/stavropol-krai. - Mod.CP

