[5] Sudan (South Darfur)
Date: Sat 2 Nov 2013
Source: Radio Dabanga [edited]
https://www.radiodabanga.org/node/58229


In South Darfur's El Serif camp for the displaced, Medecins Sans Frontieres (Belgium) has reported 4 suspected cases of measles. Samples have been taken for laboratory testing.

A highly contagious disease, measles remains one of the leading causes of death among young children globally, despite the availability of a safe and effective vaccine. Overcrowding in the Darfur camps for the displaced greatly increases the risk of infection, according to the World Health Organisation.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[South Darfur is one of the wilayat, or states, of Sudan. It is one of the 5 states that comprise the region of Darfur in western Sudan. Prior to the creation of 2 new states in the Darfur region in January 2012, South Darfur had an area of 127 300 square km (49 200 square miles) and an estimated population of approximately 2 890 000 (2006). Nyala is the capital of the state. The state was affected by the 2010 Sahel famine. In the southwest corner of this state, the LRA warlord Joseph Kony is hiding.

A map of South Darfur can be accessed at: http://reliefweb.int/sites/reliefweb.int/files/resources/map_2993.pdf. - Mod.CP

A HealthMap ProMED-mail map can be accessed at http://healthmap.org/r/1A1E.]

