The Americas
-----------
[6] Brazil (travel alert)
Date: Sat 2 Nov. 2013
Source: Digital LT10, Argentina [in Spanish, trans. Mod.JT, edited]
http://www.lt10digital.com.ar/noticia/idnot/191744/viajerosadviertenporsarampionenbrasil.html


A total of 114 cases of measles have been confirmed in Brazil, 98 of them in Pernambuco, 7 in Paraiba, 5 in Sao Paulo, 2 in Mato Grosso, one in Santa Catarina, and one in the Federal District. According to the Pan American Health Organisation, Brazil had been free of measles for a period of 10 years until the 1st imported case was recorded on 21 Jan 2013. For this reason, tourists travelling [from Argentina] to Brazil should ensure that they have been vaccinated to provide protection against mumps, measles, and rubella (MMR) at least 15 days prior to their departure.

The Ministry of Health of Argentina, through the National Programme for Control of Vaccine-Preventable Diseases (PRONACEI) has reviewed the various vaccine requirements by age:
- Children 13 months to 5 years: must demonstrate one dose of MMR vaccine.
- People aged 6 to 50 years: must have documentation of at least 2 doses of measles vaccine.
- People over 50 years are considered immune.
- Those who do not have vaccination accreditation will be required to be serology- (IgG-) positive for measles and rubella.
- When in doubt, a dose of vaccine must be administered at least 10 days before traveling.

